\f1\b0 \cf0 The gut biome is interesting enough, but bacteria colonize just about every part of the body, so recently I\'92ve been studying {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://blog.richardsprague.com/2014/10/whats-in-my-microbiome.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 my uBiome mouth test results}}. The simple {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/richardsprague/uBiome"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 GitHub RuBiome utilities}} I use for analyzing my gut will work for that too, so here\'92s a short example of how I did it:\
First I {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://blog.richardsprague.com/2015/01/how-to-analyze-ubiome-sample-in-excel.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 loaded my uBiome data}} into two variables, one for each sample: June 2014 (
\f2\fs22 junMouth
\f1\fs24 ) and the other from October 2014 (
\f2\fs22 OctMouth
\f1\fs24 ), after {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://blog.richardsprague.com/2014/10/why-review-dentists.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 a visit to my dentist}}.\
Let\'92s see which species are new in the later (October) sample:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb180\sa180

\f2\fs22 \cf0 octToJunChange <-\cf4  
\f3\b \cf5 uBiome_sample_unique
\f2\b0 \cf0 (OctMouth,junMouth)
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs22 ##   count                        missing.tax_name
\f1\fs24 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs22 ## 1  3640                  bacterium NLAE-zl-P562
\f1\fs24 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs22 ## 2  2725                 Streptococcus sanguinis
\f1\fs24 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs22 ## 3  2075               Capnocytophaga gingivalis
\f1\fs24 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs22 ## 4  1969 Peptostreptococcus sp. oral clone FG014
\f1\fs24 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\fs22 ## 5  1618                 Granulicatella adiacens
\f1\fs24 \
One of those species, 
\i Streptococcus sanguinis
\i0  looks interesting. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Streptococcus_sanguinis"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 Wikipedia}} says this:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb100\sa100

\f0\i\fs20 \cf0 S. sanguinis
\i0  is a normal inhabitant of the healthy human mouth where it is particularly found in dental plaque, where it modifies the environment to make it less hospitable for other strains of Streptococcus that cause cavities, such as Streptococcus mutans.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb180\sa180

